04523nam a22007215i 9780691187471DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911874717 a10.1515/97806911874712doi  a(DE-B1597)501663  a(OCoLC)1076412072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE184.37b.A13 2001eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a305.892/40732231 aAlexander, Michael, eauthor.10aJazz Age Jews /cMichael Alexander. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tINTERLUDE:Jazz Age Economics -- tPART I. "Biznez Iz Biznez": The Arnold Rothstein Story -- tINTERLUDE: Jazz Age Politics -- tPART II. Frankfurter among the Anarchists -- tINTERLUDE: JAZZ AGE CULTURE -- tPART III. "Mammy, Don't YouKnow Me?": Al Jolson and the Jews -- tCONCLUSION: JAZZ AGE JEWS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINDEX  aBy the 1920s, Jews were--by all economic, political, and cultural measures of the day--making it in America. But as these children of immigrants took their places in American society, many deliberately identified with groups that remained excluded. Despite their success, Jews embraced resistance more than acculturation, preferring marginal status to assimilation. The stories of Al Jolson, Felix Frankfurter, and Arnold Rothstein are told together to explore this paradox in the psychology of American Jewry. All three Jews were born in the 1880s, grew up around American Jewish ghettos, married gentile women, entered the middle class, and rose to national fame. All three also became heroes to the American Jewish community for their association with events that galvanized the country and defined the Jazz Age. Rothstein allegedly fixed the 1919 World Series--an accusation this book disputes. Frankfurter defended the Italian anarchists Sacco and Vanzetti. Jolson brought jazz music to Hollywood for the first talking film, The Jazz Singer, and regularly impersonated African Americans in blackface. Each of these men represented a version of the American outsider, and American Jews celebrated them for it. Michael Alexander's gracefully written account profoundly complicates the history of immigrants in America. It challenges charges that anti-Semitism exclusively or even mostly explains Jews' feelings of marginality, while it calls for a general rethinking of positions that have assumed an immigrant quest for inclusion into the white American mainstream. Rather, Alexander argues that Jewish outsider status stemmed from the group identity Jews brought with them to this country in the form of the theology of exile. Jazz Age Jews shows that most Jews felt culturally obliged to mark themselves as different--and believed that doing so made them both better Jews and better Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aJewszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187471zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187471.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN